    "ci_attrs": "<ul><li><a href=\"#\" data-action=\"search-by-attr\" data-crit-field=\"ci_attrs_VAR2\">DI: Area II</a></li><li><a href=\"#\" data-action=\"search-by-attr\" data-crit-field=\"ci_attrs_VAR5\">DI: Area V</a></li></ul>",
    "description": "Is war reconcilable with Christian theological and ethical commitments, or does fidelity to these commitments require some version of pacifism? Christian thinkers have debated this question for many centuries, but a common consensus across traditions has proven elusive. This seminar will explore some of the key questions and claims at stake in the debate. The course will begin by reading major Christian thinkers in the \u00c3\u00a2\u00c2\u0080\u00c2\u009cmagisterial\u00c3\u00a2\u00c2\u0080\u00c2\u009d tradition who attempt to reconcile war with basic Christian commitments. It will then look at a variety of pacifist responses to the magisterial legacy, including radical Reformation and 20th century Protestant and Catholic perspectives. Authors include Augustine, Aquinas, Luther, Calvin, Reinhold Niebuhr, Paul Ramsey, Lisa Sowle Cahill, Menno Simons, John Howard Yoder, Stanley Hauerwas, Dorothy Day, Thomas Merton, Glen Stassen and Daniel Philpott.",
